In TypeScript, you can use type guards to specify that a variable may hold multiple types in theory but will only hold one type in practice. Type guards are a powerful feature that allows you to check conditions at runtime, and they can be used to enforce type constraints in a concise manner.

Here's an example to illustrate how you can use type guards to enforce that a variable will only hold one type:

```typescript
let value: any; // Initial type variable

// Define the type you expect the variable to have in practice
function exampleUsage(value: any) {
    if (value as any!== typeSignature) {
        throw new Error("Value must be of type 'any' in practice");
    }
}

// Type guard to enforce the expected type
if (value as any) {
    value as someExpectedType; // Use the expected type here
}

function someExpectedType() {
    // Function that matches the expected type
}

// Example usage:
const expectedValue: any = 42;
exampleUsage(expectedValue as any); // This is valid

const invalidExpectedValue: any = "42";
exampleUsage(invalidExpectedValue as any); // This will throw an error
```

In this example:

1. `value` is initially of type `any`, indicating that it may hold any type in theory.
2. The `exampleUsage` function checks if the value is of type `any`. If it is not, it throws an error.
3. The type guard `if (value as any)` ensures that `value` is actually of the expected type in practice. If it is not, the function will throw an error, enforcing the type constraint.

This approach allows you to specify in theory that the variable might hold multiple types, but in practice, you can enforce that it only holds one specific type.

